topic: Sport Workflow Series ("Olympic Games explorative search")

goals.1: Identify the BGP for Olympic Games
goals.2: Return all the editions of the Summer Olympic Games (do not consider future Olympic Games) with the country where they were played (the result set must be a list of elements with edition IRI and label, and country IRI and label).
goals.3: Find the countries which held more than 2 Olympic Games (both Summer and Winter Games, do not consider future Olympic Games) (the result set must be a list of triples country IRI, label and #edition held).
goals.4: Consider the 2008 Summer Olympic Games. Identify all the sports played in this edition (the result set must be a list of couples sport IRI and label).
goals.5: Consider the 2008 Summer Olympic Games. For each sport return the number of different disciplines (the result set must be a list of triples sport IRI, label and #disciplines).
goals.6: Consider the 2008 Summer Olympic Games. Find the top-10 people who won more gold medals (the result set must be a list of triples athlete IRI, label and #gold medal).
goals.7: Find athletes who won at least one gold medal in 4 different editions of the Summer Olympic Games (the result set must be a list of triples athlete IRI, label and #edition).
goals.8: Consider all the edition of the Summer Olympic Games. For each sport return the athlete who won more gold medal (the result set must be a list of elements with sport IRI and label, athlete IRI and label, and #gold medal).

1.narrative: starting from Usain Bolt use the property participant in (P1344) and look for Olympic
1.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?obj ?name WHERE { wd:Q1189 wdt:P1344 ?obj. ?obj sc:name ?name . FILTER(REGEX(?name,"[O,o]lympic")). }
output: athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics – men's 200 metres
athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics – men's 200 metres

athletics at the 2016 Summer Olympics – men's 100 metres
athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics – men's 100 metres
athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics – men's 100 metres
athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics – men's 4 × 100 metres relay

1.narrative: see the properties of these entities

1.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?x ?name WHERE { wd:Q734020 wdt:P361 ?x. ?x sc:name ?name . }
SELECT DISTINCT ?y ?name WHERE { wd:Q734020 wdt:P361 ?x. ?x wdt:P361 ?y. ?y sc:name ?name . }
SELECT DISTINCT ?x ?name WHERE { wd:Q8577 wdt:P31 ?x. ?x sc:name ?name . }
SELECT DISTINCT ?x ?name WHERE { wd:Q159821 wdt:P279 ?x. ?x sc:name ?name . }

2.narrative:
insert the result of TASK 1 in the file
list the Summer Olympic
2.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?prop ?name WHERE { ?x wdt:P31 wd:Q159821. ?x ?prop ?y. ?prop sc:name ?name . }
output: located in the administrative territorial entity
on focus list of Wikimedia project
National Historical Museums of Sweden agent ID

2.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?x ?name ?loc ?location WHERE { ?x wdt:P31 wd:Q159821; wdt:P17 ?loc; wdt:P585 ?y. FILTER(year(?y) < 2022). ?x sc:name ?name . ?loc sc:name ?location. }
output: United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland

3.narrative:
add the elements to the JSON gt
find Summer and Winter Olympic Games
3.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?x ?name WHERE { ?x wdt:P279 wd:Q5389. ?x sc:name ?name . }

3.narrative: find Summer and Winter Olympic Games
3.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?p ?name WHERE { VALUES ?games {wd:Q159821 wd:Q82414}. ?x wdt:P31 ?games; ?p ?d. FILTER(isLiteral(?d)). FILTER(REGEX(?name,"time") OR REGEX(?name,"date") ). ?p sc:name ?name . } ORDER BY ?name

3.narrative: find Summer and Winter Olympic Games
3.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?x ?name YEAR(?d) WHERE { VALUES ?games {wd:Q159821 wd:Q82414}. ?x wdt:P31 ?games; wdt:P585 ?d. ?x sc:name ?name . } ORDER BY ?name

3.narrative: find Summer and Winter Olympic Games
3.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?country ?name COUNT(?x) AS ?olGames WHERE { VALUES ?games {wd:Q159821 wd:Q82414}. ?x wdt:P31 ?games; wdt:P585 ?d; wdt:P17 ?country. ?country sc:name ?name . FILTER(?d < NOW()). } GROUP BY ?country ?name HAVING ( COUNT(?x) > 2 )

4.narrative: find properties of this edition (2008 edition Q8567)
find properties of this edition (2008 edition Q8567)
4.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?prop ?name WHERE { wd:Q8567 wdt:P527 ?x . ?x ?prop ?y. ?prop sc:name ?name . }
output: sports season of league or competition
on focus list of Wikimedia project

4.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?y ?name WHERE { wd:Q8567 wdt:P527 ?x . ?x wdt:P641 ?y. ?y sc:name ?name . }

5.narrative: find properties of this edition (2008 edition Q8567)
5.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?sport ?name COUNT(?disc) AS ?disciplines WHERE { wd:Q8567 wdt:P527 ?x . ?x wdt:P527 ?disc; wdt:P641 ?sport. ?sport sc:name ?name . } GROUP BY ?sport ?name

6.narrative: find how people are connected with disciplines
6.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?prop ?name WHERE { wd:Q8567 wdt:P527 ?x . ?x wdt:P527 ?disc; wdt:P641 ?sport. ?athl wdt:P31 wd:Q5. ?athl ?prop ?disc. ?prop sc:name ?name . }

6.narrative: find how people are connected with disciplines
6.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?prop ?name WHERE { wd:Q8567 wdt:P527 ?x . ?x wdt:P527 ?disc; wdt:P641 ?sport. ?athl wdt:P31 wd:Q5. ?disc ?prop ?athl. ?prop sc:name ?name . }

6.narrative: return athletes with their gold medals
6.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?athl ?name COUNT(?disc) AS ?gold WHERE { wd:Q8567 wdt:P527 ?x . ?x wdt:P527 ?disc; wdt:P641 ?sport. ?athl wdt:P31 wd:Q5. ?disc wdt:P1346 ?athl. ?athl sc:name ?name . } GROUP BY ?athl ?name HAVING (COUNT(?disc) > 1) ORDER BY DESC (COUNT(?disc))

7.narrative: return athletes who won a gold medals in more than 3 editions
7.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?athl ?name COUNT(DISTINCT ?edition) AS ?gold WHERE { ?edition wdt:P31 wd:Q159821. ?edition wdt:P527 ?x . ?x wdt:P527 ?disc; wdt:P641 ?sport. ?athl wdt:P31 wd:Q5. ?disc wdt:P1346 ?athl. ?athl sc:name ?name . } GROUP BY ?athl ?name HAVING (COUNT(DISTINCT ?edition) > 3)

8.narrative:
find the athletes that have won more gold medals divided by sport
this is a quite complex solution, but I couldn't manage to find an easier one
it also returns multiple athletes for each sport since it could happen that they have the same amount of gold medals
8.query: SELECT DISTINCT ?sport ?s_name ?athlete ?a_name ?golds WHERE { FILTER(?golds = ?max_golds) { SELECT DISTINCT ?sport ?s_name ?athlete ?a_name (COUNT(*) as ?golds) ?max_golds WHERE { ?edition wdt:P31 wd:Q159821 . ?event wdt:P361 ?edition . ?discipline wdt:P361 ?event ; wdt:P1346 ?athlete ; wdt:P641 ?sport . ?athlete sc:name ?a_name . { SELECT DISTINCT ?sport ?s_name (MAX(?golds) as ?max_golds) WHERE { { SELECT DISTINCT ?sport ?athlete (COUNT(*) AS ?golds) WHERE { ?edition wdt:P31 wd:Q159821 . ?event wdt:P361 ?edition . ?discipline wdt:P361 ?event ; wdt:P1346 ?athlete ; wdt:P641 ?sport . ?athlete wdt:P31 wd:Q5 . ?discipline sc:name ?d_name . FILTER(!regex(?d_name, "qualification$")) } GROUP BY ?sport ?athlete } ?sport sc:name ?s_name . } GROUP BY ?sport ?s_name } } GROUP BY ?sport ?s_name ?athlete ?a_name ?max_golds } } ORDER BY DESC(?sport) LIMIT 100
output: John Jacob Astor, 1st Baron Astor of Hever
